wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the project overview focused on the homologacion-ukuvi system. Explain its purpose of unifying vehicle catalog data from 11 Mexican insurance providers into a canonical model with traceability and status control. Describe the core objectives, target audience (data engineers, backend developers, integration specialists), and high-level system architecture. Cover key concepts such as canonical data modeling, idempotent batch processing, and hash-based deduplication. Use diagrams from WARP.md to illustrate data flow and system context. Include a brief explanation of how the components interact, emphasizing the role of Supabase, n8n, and insurer-specific normalization workflows. Provide real-world use cases and business value. Make this section accessible to newcomers while setting the foundation for deeper technical exploration.

Explain the Progressive Enhancement pattern where data quality improves across processing cycles. Include trade-offs, failure modes, and performance implications of each pattern. Provide code examples from Supabase RPC functions and normalization scripts to illustrate implementation.

wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: Vehicle Catalog Homologation System

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
The vehicle catalog homologation system unifies vehicle catalogs from multiple Mexican insurance companies into a single canonical model. This system enables consistent vehicle data representation across insurers while maintaining complete traceability and active/inactive status control.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Create a unified canonical model for vehicle data from 11 insurance providers
- Implement a reproducible ingestion and update flow using n8n and Supabase
- Maintain complete traceability of each vehicle record back to its original insurer source
- Track active/inactive status per insurer with global validity derived from insurer reports
- Ensure idempotent processing that prevents data duplication or unintended changes

### Target Audience
- Insurance technology teams managing vehicle catalog data
- Data engineers implementing data integration pipelines
- Backend developers working with Supabase and PostgreSQL
- Data analysts requiring consistent vehicle data across insurers
- System architects designing data homogenization solutions

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The system follows a data pipeline architecture with three main components: data extraction and normalization, storage and API, and analysis and validation.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Insurance Company DBs] --> B[n8n Extraction]
    B --> C[Normalization & Hash Generation]
    C --> D[Deduplication by id_canonico]
    D --> E[Batch Creation 10k-50k records]
    E --> F[Supabase RPC Call]
    F --> G[catalogo_homologado Table]
    G --> H[Availability JSONB per Insurer]
    
    I[MCP Analysis Agents] --> A
    I --> J[Profiling & Validation]
    J --> K[Mapping Suggestions]
```

### Design Patterns
The system implements several key design patterns:

1. **Canonical Data Model**: All insurer data is transformed into a unified schema with standardized fields
2. **Event Sourcing for Availability**: The `disponibilidad` JSONB field maintains a history of status changes per insurer
3. **Idempotent Processing**: The RPC function is designed to produce the same results when called multiple times with the same input
4. **Hash-Based Deduplication**: Uses SHA-256 hashes (`id_canonico` and `hash_comercial`) to identify and deduplicate records
5. **Progressive Enhancement**: The system can enrich existing records with additional technical specifications from new insurer data

### System Relationships
The components interact through well-defined interfaces:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Insurer Databases] -->|SQL Queries| B[Insurer-Specific Analysis]
    B -->|Normalization Rules| C[n8n Workflows]
    C -->|JSON Payloads| D[Supabase RPC]
    D -->|PostgreSQL Functions| E[catalogo_homologado]
    E -->|Data Validation| F[MCP Analysis Agents]
    F -->|Mapping Suggestions| B
```

### Data Flow
The data flows through the system in a structured pipeline:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Source Data] --> B[Extraction]
    B --> C[Normalization]
    C --> D[Hash Generation]
    D --> E[Deduplication]
    E --> F[Batching]
    F --> G[RPC Processing]
    G --> H[Persistence]
    H --> I[Query Interface]
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- **n8n workflows**: Orchestrate the extraction, transformation, and loading process
- **Supabase RPC function**: `procesar_batch_homologacion` handles batch processing
- **Analysis markdown files**: Document insurer-specific patterns and rules

Sources:
- [instrucciones.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/instrucciones.md)
- [WARP.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/WARP.md)

### Core Modules
- **Insurer-specific normalization**: Each insurer has dedicated analysis and code files
- **Supabase database schema**: Defines the canonical model and processing logic
- **Hash generation and deduplication**: Core logic for creating unique identifiers

Sources:
- [src/insurers](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/insurers)
- [src/supabase](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/supabase)

### Configuration Approach
The system uses a combination of code-based configuration and database schema definitions:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Environment Variables] --> B[n8n Workflows]
    C[SQL Schema Files] --> D[Supabase Database]
    E[Markdown Analysis] --> F[Normalization Rules]
    F --> B
    D --> G[RPC Functions]
```

Sources:
- [WARP.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/WARP.md#L100-L150)
- [src/supabase/Tabla maestra.sql](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/supabase/Tabla%20maestra.sql)

### External Dependencies
- **Supabase**: PostgreSQL database with PostgREST API
- **n8n**: Workflow automation platform for data orchestration
- **MCP agents**: Analysis tools for data profiling and validation

Sources:
- [instrucciones.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/instrucciones.md#L1-L50)
- [WARP.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/WARP.md#L20-L30)

### Integration Points
- **Database connections**: Direct SQL access to insurer databases
- **Supabase RPC**: REST endpoint for batch processing
- **n8n HTTP nodes**: Integration with Supabase API

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Insurer DBs] -->|JDBC/ODBC| B[Extraction]
    B -->|JSON| C[n8n]
    C -->|HTTP POST| D[Supabase RPC]
    D -->|PostgreSQL| E[Database]
```

Sources:
- [instrucciones.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/instrucciones.md#L100-L150)
- [src/supabase/Funcion RPC Nueva.sql](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/supabase/Funcion%20RPC%20Nueva.sql)

### Component Relationships
The system components are organized in a layered architecture:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Data Sources] --> B[Extraction Layer]
    B --> C[Transformation Layer]
    C --> D[Integration Layer]
    D --> E[Persistence Layer]
    E --> F[Analysis Layer]
    F --> C
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
The system provides comprehensive vehicle catalog homologation with several key features:

1. **Multi-insurer support**: Handles data from 11 different insurance companies
2. **Canonical modeling**: Transforms diverse data formats into a unified schema
3. **Status tracking**: Maintains active/inactive status per insurer
4. **Idempotent processing**: Ensures consistent results across multiple executions
5. **Data provenance**: Preserves original data and mapping information

### Implementation Highlights
The implementation includes sophisticated normalization logic for handling insurer-specific data patterns:

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> Extracting: Start Process
    Extracting --> Normalizing: Data Retrieved
    Normalizing --> Deduplicating: Text Cleaned
    Deduplicating --> Batching: Hashes Generated
    Batching --> Processing: Batch Created
    Processing --> Success: RPC Complete
    Processing --> Error: Validation Failed
    Success --> Idle: Complete
    Error --> Idle: Complete with Warnings
```

Sources:
- [src/insurers/qualitas/qualitas-analisis.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/insurers/qualitas/qualitas-analisis.md)
- [src/insurers/hdi/hdi-analisis.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/insurers/hdi/hdi-analisis.md)
- [src/insurers/gnp/gnp-analisis.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/src/insurers/gnp/gnp-analisis.md)

### Feature Architecture
The feature architecture supports flexible expansion to new insurers:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[New Insurer] --> B[Analysis Phase]
    B --> C[Pattern Identification]
    C --> D[Normalization Rules]
    D --> E[Extraction Query]
    E --> F[Testing]
    F --> G[Production]
    G --> H[Monitoring]
```

Sources:
- [WARP.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/WARP.md#L200-L250)
- [instrucciones.md](/Users/eduardojaviergarcialopez/TendencIA/homologacion-ukuvi/instrucciones.md#L300-L350)
</blog>
